Oil Volatility Falls as Futures Jump on Move by Central Banks

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-09-15T18:26:59Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-15/oil-volatility-falls-as-futures-jump-on-move-by-central-banks.html
Oil options volatility fell as the
underlying futures increased after the  European Central Bank 
announced it will lend euro-area banks dollars to help tame the
regionâ€™s credit crisis in coordination with the  Federal Reserve 
and other central banks.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
November, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options prices, was 37.7 percent at 2 p.m. in  New York ,
down from 39 percent yesterday.  Oil for October delivery rose 66 cents, or 0.7 percent, to
$89.57 a barrel at 2:13 p.m. on the  New York Mercantile
Exchange . Oil has fallen 2 percent this year. Crude for November
delivery gained 69 cents to $89.70.  The most active contract in electronic trading today was
October $90 calls, with 3,923 lots changing hands. The options
dropped 34 cents to 4 cents a barrel. October options expire at
the close of Nymex floor trading today. One contract covers
1,000 barrels of crude.  November $60 puts were the most active options among those
without an October strike price. The contract slipped 4 cents to
11 cents on volume of 1,066 lots.  Puts outnumbered calls by 51 percent to 49 percent.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information on floor trading, where the
bulk of options trading occur the next business day.  November $115 calls were the most active options traded in
the previous session, with 7,501 lots changing hands. They fell
3 cents to 10 cents a barrel. The next-most active options,
October $90 calls, retreated 85 cents to 38 cents a barrel on
volume of 7,133.  Open interest was highest for December $100 calls with
51,330 contracts. Next were December $70 puts with 45,588 and
December $50 puts with 45,300.  To contact the reporter on this story:
